      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about how bread gets that nice brown color on the crust and i think it's called the maillard reaction? can u explain how that actually works and what temps i need to look out for so i dont burn everything?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction is responsible for the browning of bread crusts. It's a non-enzymatic browning reaction between amino acids and reducing sugars when exposed to heat, resulting in the formation of new flavor compounds and the characteristic golden-brown color. Typically, temperatures between 160°C to 180°C (320°F to 356°F) stimulate the Maillard reaction, which is why it's often triggered by baking or toasting bread. By monitoring your oven's temperature and regulating it, you can achieve a nicely browned crust without burning the bread.",
