    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. so is it just about the heat, or do the specific types of sugars and proteins matter too? like does using honey vs white sugar change how fast it browns?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction involves specific combinations of amino acids, reducing sugars, and other compounds present in the dough, rather than just heat alone. The type and amount of sugars and proteins do indeed play a role in determining the color and flavor of the browning reaction. Honey, for example, contains more moisture and certain amino acids than white sugar, which can affect the browning rate and resulting flavor. Sugar types like honey, maple syrup, or brown sugar tend to produce a richer, darker brown color than white sugar. Ambient moisture and enzyme activity also influence the Maillard reaction, making small variations in dough composition significant.",
